10.body: Hello World: compact source vs standard Java structure We're only using compact source in lecture Requires --enable-preview in Java 24 Allowed by default in Java 25 Explain parts of program: main(): function, entry point void: keyword, return type {}: code block IO: namespacing println(): function "Hello World": strings

11.title: Variables

12.body: Input and Output (I/O) On terminal (standard in, standard out) Standard out example: ls Standard in (and out) example: jshell Java I/O functions: IO.readln(prompt) IO.println(message) IO.print(message) Store input in variables Write a program that repeats user input
12.title: I/O

13.body: Challenging to think about programs: What goes in your code? What does the computer do for you? What information does the user provide? Common mistake: writing user input in your code Three roles to consider: Programmers write instructions Computers follow instructions Users break things provide input To write good instructions, you need to think about how the computer will follow them and how the user will interact with your program. However, none of that actually goes in your code!
13.breadcrumbs: Week 2 » The Program, Computer, and User » The Program, Computer, and User
13.title: The Program, Computer, and User

14.body: Computers are complicated. How do we understand what they're doing? What can we do that's similar to the following: IO.println IO.readln var x = ... x = ... Easier to understand programs if you can imagine how you would execute their instructions.

15.body: Write a hello world program from scratch. Don't look at any code, but feel free to check your notes if you forgot how to do something. Experiement with the Greeting.java program and find an answer to each of the questions in the comments. Update the Home.java program so that it works for everyone in this classroom. You're only allowed nine lines of code inside the main function: the eight prints/printlns and one variable. Hint: you need to read user input when you create the variable. Finish the Email.java program. It should be able to print your QU email in the "firstname.lastname@quinnipiac.edu" format.

18.body: What is a type? Three new types: String, int, double Others that we'll cover later: byte, short, long, float, char, boolean Variables have types, Java uses "static typing" var keyword infers type from initial value

19.title: Syntax

20.body: Explicit types preferred in Java, avoid var Syntax: declare, initialize, reassign Common mistake: redeclare (illegal) instead of reassign Assignment operator (=) does not mean what you think it means Remember static typing?
20.title: Variables

21.body: Implicit, cast, and functions Implicit conversions: anything to String int to double Explicit conversion (cast): double to int With functions: String parsing into int or double
21.title: Conversions

22.body: Arithmetic operators: +, -, *, / Modulo/remainder operator: % Unary operators: +, - Integer division Overflow Doubles have limited precision Literals: Underscores for readability Scientific notation Math functions: Math.pow Math.abs Math.min and Math.max
22.title: Numbers

23.body: Concatenation: + What is a method? String methods: toUpperCase() and toLowerCase() substring(start) and substring(start, end) length() Indexes for substring Zero-indexing Upper bound is exclusive
23.title: Strings

24.body: Stuff from class will be in a public git repository Can download a zip on GitHub, but this is a pain Easier: clone/pull on terminal using git Git installation Linux: use package manager, probably have it already Mac: https://git-scm.com/downloads/mac Windows: already got it when you installed Git Bash If you don't have the repo yet, then you can clone it with the following command. Run this command from inside your csc110 folder! git clone git@github.com:zachkohlberg/csc11025fa_class_repo.git If you already have the repo, then you can update it with the following command. Run this command from inside the cloned repo! git pull Avoid storing your own files in the repo or editing the files in the repo. If you modify anything in the repo, then you may run into errors when you try to update it with the pull command.
24.breadcrumbs: Week 3 » Class Git Repo » Class Git Repo
24.title: Class Git Repo

25.body: Experiment with the Arithmetic.java program and answer the questions in the comments. Try writing a program that generates a shorter school email address: fmlast@quinnipiac.edu (first initial, middle initial, last name) instead of first.last@quinnipiac.edu. Ask for the user's first name, middle initial, last name, and school name. Use toLowerCase to ensure nothing is capitalized, and use substring to get the user's first initial. Try writing a program that calculates the total minutes from a number of days, hours, and minutes. For example, if a user inputs 4 days, 17 hours, and 11 minutes, then the program should respond with "6791 total minutes." Try writing a program that does the opposite of the previous program: take a number of minutes and convert it to days, hours, and minutes. For example, if a user inputs 6791 minutes, then the program should respond with "4 days, 17 hours, and 11 minutes." This process is similar to the Height.java program.
